com.camerontec.catalys.core.session

Class Session

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.catalys.util.configuration.AbstractConfigurable
      • com.camerontec.catalys.core.session.Session
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IConfigurable, IRegisterable, Runnable

    public class Session
extends AbstractConfigurable
implements Runnable
    All FIX communication takes place through a Session object. A session represents a logical connection between two communicating parties. Each session is associated with a physical connection between the two parties - represented by an associated Connection object.

    Establishing a FIX session involves:

    1. Establishing a physical connection between the two parties - for example, a TCP/IP connection.
    2. Creating a Session object associated with that physical connection.
    3. Starting that Session object using start().
    4. Exchanging messages using the SendManager.send(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage, boolean, boolean) and getMessage() methods of the Session object.

    Fires the following events:

    • All Session related events in ICatalysEventType

    Implementation Notes

    Threads:

    These are the threads in operation:

    1. User thread(s).

    The user will have at least one thread.

    Typically he will have two:

    • the thread that sends messages by calling the send(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage) method.
    • the thread that processes messages by calling the getMessage() and processedMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage) methods.
    However, he could equally well run in a single thread with code like: 
              if (session.gotMessage()) {
            try {
              Message mess = session.getMessage();
              try {
                ...Process mess
              } catch (Exception ex) {
                ...handle processing exception
              }
              session.processedMessage( mess );
            } catch (Exception ex) {
              ...Process exception
            }
         } else {
           if ( got_something_to_send ) {
             session.send( message_to_send );
           }
         }
 ;

    2. Protocol thread.

    This thread manages the actual protocol. It processes received messages, adding user messages (ie all messages except administrative messages like heartbeats) to the appQ. The user removes message from the appQ by calling getMessage().

    3. Message Assembler thread.

    This thread processes received bytes, formatting them up into proper messages to be processed by the protocol thread. It communicates with the protocol thread by calling the session object's update method. This method puts the passed message or exception onto the inQ.

    4. Heartbeat thread.

    This sends out a heartbeat message at regular intervals.

    Queues:

    Messages and exceptions received are assembled and put into inQ in the order received.

    The protocol logic reads from inQ.

    The protocol logic puts in-sequence messages directly onto appQ.

    The application reads this queue by calling getMessage().

    The application signals that a message has been processed by calling processedMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage).

    Exceptions which have occurred that the user might be interested in are also queued on the appQ.

    Calling getMessage() will throw the exception if it is the next entry on the queue.

    The protocol logic saves out-of-sequence messages in gapQ.

    When the missing messages are filled in, the protocol logic processes the correctly sequenced messages and they are transferred from gapQ to appQ.

    Admin messages from application level (such as login/logout) get put into adminQ. The protocol logic thread picks things off adminQ and processes them.

      • Session

        public Session(Connection conn,
               IFIXSessionStatePersister persister,
               Crypto crypto)
        throws CryptoException,
               IOException
        Create session object associated with given physical connection, persistence and encryption objects.

        Communication does not actually take place over a session until the start() or start(int, int) is called.

        The input and output sequence numbers are recovered from the persistence object.
        If you need to override the sequence numbers you should start the session using start(int, int).

        Parameters:
        conn - Connection over which session is held
        persister - Persistence object. If null defaults to a MemorySeqNoOnlyPersister.
        crypto - Instance of Crypto object used for encryption. If null, default encryption is used.
        Throws:
        CryptoException - if there is an encryption setup problem
        IOException - if there is a problem with the Connection or the persistence.

        This constructor is handy for core library applications to use if they know the session ids (i.e. ConnectionPoint) instead of the comparable constructors without a connectionPoint parameter.

        The problem with those constructors (without connectionPoint parameter) is that a warning message is displayed when they are added to the SessionFactory.

        persister - Persistence object. If null defaults to a MemorySeqNoOnlyPersister.
        crypto - Instance of Crypto object used for encryption
        Throws:
        CryptoException - if there is an encryption setup problem

      • isLogonPassThroughEnabled

        public boolean isLogonPassThroughEnabled()
        Returns:
        whether logon pass though mode is enabled. In this mode, the session passes the logon message though to the next level (e.g., the caller of getMessage()). If the next level responds by sending back a Logon message (e.g., via send(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage)) then we are logged on. If a logout message is sent back then we are logged out.

      • addMessageProcessingInfo

        public void addMessageProcessingInfo(MessageProcessingInfo info)
                              throws NonFatalProtocolException
        Adds special message processing characteristics.

        By default all message types may be processed internally. Also, all message types are exposed (ie passed up to the application program) except for the following:

        • Heartbeats
        • Resend requests
        • Sequence resets
        • Test requests
        If an application wanted to receive heartbeats for a Session it should do the following: MessageProcessingInfo info; info = new MessageProcessingInfo( MsgType.Heartbeat.value ); info.setExposed( true ); addMessageProcessingInfo( info ) Normally the only applications that would want to turn off internal processing of messages would be FIX compliance testing applications that wish to modify the standard FIX protocol in order to test how other FIX engines handle protocol errors. Not all combinations of characteristics are allowed in normal operation. For example, it is not permitted to disable internal message processing for unexposed messages.
        These restrictions can be removed by using setStrictMode(boolean) to turn off strict mode operation.
        Parameters:
        info - Requested message processing characteristics.
        Throws:
        NonFatalProtocolException - if the requested characteristics are not permitted.
        See Also:
        MessageProcessingInfo, getMessageProcessingInfo(java.lang.String)

      • getMessage

        public IFIXMessage getMessage()
                       throws InterruptedException,
                              IOException,
                              LogonException,
                              MessageException,
                              MessageParsingException,
                              ProtocolException
        Call this method to get data for processing.

        Once processing of the data has been attempted you should call processedMessage(com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage). Note that even if processing raised an exception, processedMessage should still be called.

        If there is nothing on the input queue this method will block until something arrives.

        If you do not want to block, use the gotMessage method to check there is something there first. For example: 

        
 if (session.gotMessage()) {
   try {
     IFIXMessage mess = session.getMessage();
     try {
       // ...Process mess
     } catch (Exception ex) {
       // ...handle processing exception
     }
     session.processedMessage( mess );
   } catch (Exception ex) {
     // ...Process exception
   }
 }

        May be called simultaneously by multiple processing threads.

        Returns:
        the next message
        Throws:
        InterruptedException - if this thread has been interrupted. Since this would normally be triggered by the user code, whether or not it should be regarded as fatal is up to the programmer.
        IOException - if Connection was lost. This is a fatal error and the session is closed.
        LogonException - if a logon attempt failed (eg timed out waiting for Logon response
        MessageException - if a badly formatted message was received
        MessageParsingException - if a badly formatted message was received
        ProtocolException - TBD
        NonFatalProtocolException - if a recoverable protocol error occurred.
        FatalProtocolException - if a unrecoverable protocol error occurred. This is a fatal error and the session is closed.
        See Also:
        getMessage(long)

      • getMessage

        public IFIXMessage getMessage(long timeout)
                       throws InterruptedException,
                              IOException,
                              LogonException,
                              MessageException,
                              MessageParsingException,
                              ProtocolException
        A variant of getMessage() which supports a timed block.
        Parameters:
        timeout - The timeout in milliseconds. If this is zero or negative then the behaviour is as for getMessage(). If this is positive then the caller is blocked for at most the specified number of milliseconds for a message to arrive. If no such message arrives then this method returns null.
        Returns:
        The next inbound message, or null if no message arrived within the specified timeout period.
        Throws:
        InterruptedException - See getMessage()
        IOException - See getMessage()
        LogonException - See getMessage()
        MessageException - See getMessage()
        MessageParsingException - See getMessage()
        ProtocolException - See getMessage()

      • processedMessage

        public void processedMessage(IFIXMessage mess)
                      throws IOException
        Call this to indicate that processing of a message has been completed.

        By calling this, you are effectively saying that you will never need to see this message from FIX again. In the event of a crash, this message will not normally be resent as part of the recovery process.

        This method is used with the getMessage() method to read and process incoming FIX messages.

        The fact that this message has been processed is persisted for recovery purposes. It is the message's sequence number that is persisted. In the event of failure, the other side of the FIX connection will be asked to resend all messages from the last persisted sequence number.

        Parameters:
        mess - Message that has been processed
        Throws:
        IOException - if there was a problem persisting message sequence number.
        See Also:
        getMessage()

      • sendSessionReject

        public void sendSessionReject(ITagValues messageToReject,
                              int sessionRejectReason,
                              int tagToReject,
                              String rejectReasonText)
                       throws IOException,
                              FatalProtocolException,
                              MessageException
        Sends a FIX session reject message.

        Supports the extra rejection information fields introduced in FIX 4.2.

        Note that you can use this method even if the Session is not currently using FIX 4.2 because the extra fields will be put in the FIX Text(Tag 58) for older FIX versions.

        Unknown String parameters may be set to null in which case they will not be sent in the message. SessionRejectReason will only be set if it is >= 0.

        Note tagToReject could be specified if known but it will be set if > 0.

        Parameters:

      • reset

        public void reset()
           throws IOException
        Reset the sequence numbers of this session.

        This can only be used on a Session that is not started, ie it has never been started or it has been started but has subsequently been closed (by calling the close method).

        All output messages in the underlying persister are cleared (ie lost).

        Normally this should not be called directly. The recommended procedure for resetting sequence numbers is described in the FIX specification. (See the Logon discussion in the Session Protocol section of the FIX specification). The recommendation is to use the ResetSeqNumFlag field in a Logon message to request a sequence number reset. That way, both parties are automatically in sync.

        However, sometimes it may be necessary to coordinate the sequence reset manually. That is, both parties agree to manually reset sequence numbers on their respective FIX engines. This method would be used in such a situation.

        Throws:
        IOException - if Session is already started.

      • initiateCounterpartyDetection

        public void initiateCounterpartyDetection()
                                   throws FatalProtocolException,
                                          IOException,
                                          MissingDataException,
                                          MessageException,
                                          ConversionException,
                                          LogonException,
                                          TimedoutException,
                                          MessageIntegrityException
        Master (logon initiator) calls this to initiate the counterparty detection onEntry.

        Send special test request and wait for heartbeat response, then execute strategy. Counterparty capabilities should have been received and stored by then if it is a Catalys counterparty.

        Logic: 

                                                                    Lock out other output
                                                            MessageAssembler.setReadOnDemand( true );
         --> send our capabilities (TR m)
         <-- receive counterparty capabilities (TR them)
                                                            Store counterparty capabilities
         --> Ack counterparty capabilities (HB TR them)
         <-- Counterparty acks our capabilities (HB TR us)
                                                            Select and activate strategy
                                                            MessageAssembler.setReadOnDemand( false );
        Throws:
        FatalProtocolException - TBD

      • setStrictMode

        public void setStrictMode(boolean strictMode)
        Can be used to relax strict enforcement of the FIX protocol.

        WARNING: Normally you should never call this.

        This method is included for testing purposes and, in particular, for the use of FIX certification applications. Such applications have the unusual requirement of needing to artificially generate protocol error conditions in order to test whether the FIX engine being tested handles those errors correctly.

        Sessions automatically start and run in strict mode. Use this call only if you do not want to operate in strict mode.

        While not running in strict mode, the checksum field, which is normally populated automatically, is set only if it does not already exist in the message being sent. This allows the application to set a non standard value in this field.

        WARNING AGAIN: Don't be surprised if the protocol doesn't work as expected if you are not running in strict mode!

        Parameters:
        strictMode - False if you want to relax strict FIX protocol enforcement.

      • start

        public void start()
           throws IOException
        Start communication on this Session.

        This used to be implicit when a Session was created. The advantage of having separate start methods is that it provides a controlled way of overriding the default sequence numbers at startup. Default sequence numbers are recovered from a Session's IFIXSessionStatePersister object. However, sometimes it is necessary to manually override those sequence numbers. This should be done before communication has actually commenced - ie before the Logon sequence. Overriding sequence numbers is achieved by calling start(int, int) instead of this method.

        It would have been possible to provide public "set" methods for setting the sequence numbers. However, this is too dangerous. It is not acceptable in the FIX protocol to arbitrarily set sequence numbers at any time. Changing sequence numbers must be done in a strictly controlled fashion in order to ensure that no messages are inadvertently lost.
        See the FIX specification Administrative Messages section on the Logon and SequenceReset messages as well as the general comments on the Logon process in the Session Protocol section.

        Throws:
        IOException - if Session is already started or if there is no Connection or if there are other Connection problems.

      • start

        public void start(int inMsgSeqNum,
                  int outMsgSeqNum)
           throws IOException
        Use this to override the session's sequence numbers and then start communication.

        Normally you should use start() instead. See documentation on that method for further details.

        Sequence numbers of less than or equal to zero are ignored.

        Parameters:
        inMsgSeqNum - If greater than 0, then this overrides sequence number.
        outMsgSeqNum - If greater than 0, then this overrides sequence number.
        Throws:
        IOException - if Session is already started or if there is no Connection or if there are other Connection problems.

        public void configure(IConfiguration configuration)

        Description copied from interface: IConfigurable
        Apply the IConfiguration to this IConfigurable.

        This method is called by the configuration module in the server:

        • when loading the configuration at server startup (e.g. when reading the XML configuration file) and
